04991nam a22006735i 9780823237975DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232379757 a10.1515/97808232379752doi  a(DE-B1597)555137  a(OCoLC)647876388  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aML193b.M88 2009 7aMUS0200002bisacsh04a781/.122300aMusical Meaning and Human Values /cLawrence Kramer, Keith Chapin. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (226 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Examples and Figures -- tIntroduction -- t1. Due Rose, Due Volte: A Study of Early Modern Subjectivities -- t2. Sublime Experience and Ironic Action: E. T. A. Hoffmann and the Use of Music for Life -- t3. The Devoted Ear: Music as Contemplation -- t4. Music and Fantasy -- t5. Whose Brahms Is It Anyway? Observations on the Recorded Legacy of the B/, Piano Concerto, Op. 83 -- t6. The Civilizing Process: Music and the Aesthetics of Time- Space Relations in The Girl of the Golden West -- t7. A Farewell, a Femme Fatale, and a Film: Three Awkward Moments in Twentieth-Century Music -- t8. ''Pour Out . . . Forgiveness Like a Wine'': Can Music ''Say an Existence Is Wrong''? -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex of Works 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMusical understanding has evolved dramatically in recent years, principally through a heightened appreciation of musical meaning in its social, cultural, and philosophical dimensions. This collection of essays by leading scholars addresses an aspect of meaning that has not yet received its due: the relation of meaning in this broad humanistic sense to the shaping of fundamental values. The volume examines the open and active circle between the values and valuations placed on music by both individuals and societies, and the discovery, through music, of what and how to value.With a combination of cultural criticism and close readings of musical works, the contributors demonstrate repeatedly that to make music is also to make value, in every sense. They give particular attention to values that have historically enabled music to assume a formative role in human societies: to foster practices of contemplation, fantasy, and irony; to explore sexuality, subjectivity, and the uncanny; and to articulate longings for unity with nature and for moral certainty. Each essay in the collection shows, in its own way, how music may provoke transformative reflection in its listeners and thus help guide humanity to its own essential embodiment in the world.The range of topics is broad and developed with an eye both to the historical specificity of values and to the variety of their possible incarnations. The music is both canonical and noncanonical, old and new. Although all of it is "classical," the contributors' treatment of it yields conclusions that apply well beyond the classical sphere. The composers discussed include Gabrieli, Marenzio, Haydn, Beethoven, Mendelssohn, Brahms, Wagner, Puccini, Hindemith, Schreker, and Henze.Anyone interested in music as it is studied today will find this volume essential reading.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aMusicxPhilosophy and aesthetics. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aChapin, Keith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKramer, Lawrence, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082323797540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823237975423Coveruhttps://www.